# Ant Design Component Custom CSS Rules

## Core Principles
- Centralized Color Management: All color definitions must be in global.css using CSS variables or theme selectors
- Minimal Implementation: Only define necessary styles, avoid duplicating default settings
- Theme Consistency: Dark/light modes must be handled separately, never use fixed color values

## Implementation Steps
1. Check Global Styles
   - First check if global.css already has corresponding theme color settings
   - Use existing CSS variables (e.g., var(--text-primary))
   - Leverage existing theme selectors (e.g., body[data-theme='dark'])

2. Color Handling Rules
   - Forbidden: Direct fixed color values (e.g., color: #fff)
   - Required: Use body[data-theme='dark'] and body[data-theme='light'] separately
   - Preferred: Use global CSS variables
   - Exception: Brand colors can use fixed values

3. Style Definition Scope
   - Page-specific: Layout, spacing, special effects in page CSS
   - Global scope: Common component styles in global.css
   - Avoid duplication: Don't repeat Ant Design default styles

4. Cleanup Standards
   - Remove styles with no difference from default effects
   - Eliminate hardcoded color values
   - Merge duplicate style definitions
   - Keep necessary layout and functional styles

5. Naming Conventions
   - Use semantic class names
   - Avoid conflicts with Ant Design class names
   - Keep it concise and clear